{{main|Claude Monet}} {{Infobox artwork | image_file = Monet, Claude - Charing Cross Bridge - Google Art Project.jpg | painting_alignment = | image_size = 300px | title = Charing Cross Bridge | alt = | other_language_1 = | other_title_1 = | other_language_2 = | other_title_2 = | artist = [[Claude Monet]] | year = c. 1900 | medium = [[Oil painting|Oil]] on [[canvas]] | height_metric = | width_metric = | length_metric = | height_imperial = 26 | width_imperial = 36.5 | length_imperial = | diameter__metric = | diameter_imperial = | imperial_unit = in | metric_unit = cm | city = [[Indianapolis]] | museum = [[Indianapolis Museum of Art]] | coordinates = | owner = }}
'''''Charing Cross Bridge''''' is a series of [[oil painting]]s by [[France|French]] artist [[Claude Monet]]. Painted in between 1899 and 1904, they depict a misty, [[Impressionism|impressionistic]] [[Charing Cross Bridge]] in London.
==Historical information== During the years between 1899 and 1905, Monet travelled to London to capture its sights from the fifth-floor balcony of the [[Savoy Hotel]]. Monet was captivated by the [[pea soup fog|London fog]], a notable atmospheric effect made markedly worse by the heavy pollution of the [[Industrial Revolution]]. He painted the [[Houses of Parliament series (Monet)|Houses of Parliament]], [[Waterloo Bridge]], and Charing Cross Bridge over and over, as he had earlier done with [[Haystacks (Monet)|haystacks]] and [[Rouen Cathedral (Monet)|Rouen Cathedral]], dashing off paintings to capture fleeting atmospheric effects. He was extremely prolific, beginning nearly 100 paintings in London.<ref name=lee>{{cite book|last1=Lee|first1=Ellen Wardwell|last2=Robinson|first2=Anne|title=Indianapolis Museum of Art: Highlights of the Collection|publisher=[[Indianapolis Museum of Art]]|location=[[Indianapolis]]|year=2005|isbn=0936260777}}</ref> Thirty-seven of the canvases were of Charing Cross Bridge, only twelve of which he finished in London; the rest he took back to his [[Giverny]] studio for completion.<ref name=thyssen/>
==Locations== The ''Charing Cross Bridge'' paintings are scattered in collections all around the world. The unfinished canvas held by the [[Indianapolis Museum of Art]] was once derided by [[Terry Teachout]] in the ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' as second-rate, proof that "even a master can have his off days."<ref>{{cite web|title=IMA has "second-rate art"?|url=http://eyeonindianapolis.blogspot.com/2007_03_01_archive.html|publisher=Eye on Indianapolis|accessdate=29 November 2012}}</ref> Other versions are at the [[Art Institute of Chicago]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Charing Cross Bridge, London, 1901|url=http://www.artic.edu/aic/collections/artwork/16544|publisher=[[Art Institute of Chicago]]|accessdate=29 November 2012}}</ref> the [[Baltimore Museum of Art]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Charing Cross Bridge|url=http://www.artbma.org/annualreport/2009/leadership/monet.html|publisher=[[Baltimore Museum of Art]]|accessdate=29 November 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110107200220/http://www.artbma.org/annualreport/2009/leadership/monet.html|archivedate=7 January 2011|df=}}</ref> the [[Museum of Fine Arts, Boston]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Charing Cross Bridge (overcast day), 1900|url=http://www.mfa.org/collections/object/charing-cross-bridge-overcast-day-1900-34284|publisher=[[Museum of Fine Arts, Boston]]|accessdate=29 November 2012}}</ref> the Harvard Museum of Fine Art, the [[Art Gallery of Ontario]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Claude Monet, Charing Cross Bridge, Fog|url=http://www.ago.net/claude-monet-charing-cross-bridge-fog|publisher=[[Art Gallery of Ontario]]|accessdate=29 November 2012}}</ref> and the [[Thyssen-Bornemisza Museum]]<ref name=thyssen>{{cite web|title=Claude Monet Charing Cross Bridge 1899|url=http://www.museothyssen.org/en/thyssen/ficha_obra/677|publisher=[[Thyssen-Bornemisza Museum]]|accessdate=29 November 2012}}</ref> in [[Madrid]]. One version was stolen from the [[Kunsthal]] Museum in [[Rotterdam]] on October 16, 2012<ref>{{cite web|last=Hasan|first=Lama|title=Daring Art Heist Nets Picasso, Matisse|url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/headlines/2012/10/daring-art-heist-nets-picasso-matisse/|publisher=[[ABC News]]|accessdate=29 November 2012|date=16 Oct 2012}}</ref> and is believed to have been incinerated by the mother of one of the thieves in her oven.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Vandoorne|first1=Saskya|last2=Smith-Spark|first2=Laura|last3=Ciobanu|first3=Liliana|title=Stove ashes probed for traces of stolen Picasso, Matisse, Monet works|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/07/19/world/europe/romania-stolen-art-probe|publisher=[[CNN]]|accessdate=7 August 2013|date=19 July 2013}}</ref>
==Gallery== Some of the paintings in the ''Charing Cross Bridge'' series: <gallery widths="200px" heights="200px" perrow="4"> Image:Charing Cross Bridge, Monet.jpg|''Charing Cross Bridge,'' 1899, [[Thyssen-Bornemisza Museum]] Madrid File:Claude Monet - Charing Cross Bridge (1899-1901).jpg|''Charing Cross Bridge'', c. 1899-1901, private collection File:Claude Monet - Charing Cross Bridge (Saint Louis).jpg|''Charing Cross Bridge, London'', 1899-1901, [[Saint Louis Art Museum]] Image:Charing Cross Bridge, London.jpg|''Charing Cross Bridge, London,'' 1901, Rotterdam painting Image:Claude Monet - Charing-Cross Bridge in London - Google Art Project.jpg|''Charing-Cross Bridge in London,'' c. 1902, [[National Museum of Western Art]] in [[Tokyo]] File:Monet-Tamise-Lyon.jpg|''Charing Cross Bridge,'' 1903, [[Museum of Fine Arts of Lyon]] Lyon File:Claude Monet - Charing Cross Bridge, Fog.jpg|''Charing Cross Bridge, Fog,'' 1902, [[Art Gallery of Ontario]] </gallery>
