{{Infobox Artwork | image_file=Piero di cosimo, incarnazione.jpg | title=Immaculate Conception with Saints | image_size = 420px | artist=Piero di Cosimo | year=between 1485 and 1505 | medium=Oil on panel | height_metric=206 | width_metric=172 | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | city = Florence | museum=Uffizi }} '''''The Immaculate Conception with Saints''''' (also known as ''The Incarnation of Jesus'') is a painting by the [[Italy|Italian]] [[Renaissance]] painter [[Piero di Cosimo]], executed between 1485 and 1505.<ref>[http://www.polomuseale.firenze.it/inv1890/ Uffizi Gallery (search for inventory number '506')]</ref> It is housed in the [[Uffizi Gallery]] of [[Florence]], [[Italy]].
The painting was executed for the Tebaldi Chapel in the church of [[Annunziata, Florence|the Annunziata]] of Florence, and was acquired by Cardinal [[Leopoldo de' Medici]] in 1670. It was moved to the Uffizi in 1804.<ref>Gloria Fossi, ''Galleria degli Uffizi - Arte storia collezioni'', p. 202</ref>
The work shows the Virgin in a central and illuminated position, with a dove hovering above her head. She is flanked by the Saints [[John the Apostle|John the Evangelist]], [[Philip Benizi de Damiani|Philip Benizi]], [[Catherine_of_Alexandria|Catherine]] (kneeling on the left), [[Margaret the Virgin|Margaret]] (kneeling on the right), [[Antoninus of Florence|Antoninus]] and [[Saint Peter|Peter]]. In the background is a typical Piero's landscape, with two hills characterized by rock with human and beast appearance, where the other scenes of the ''Adoration of the Magi'', the ''Annunciation to the Shepherds'' on the left and the ''Flight to Egypt'' on the right are depicted.
